segments.text: Thursday testing, testing, testing.
Testing.
One, two, three.
This is Thursday, January 10, 2002, in downtown Albuquerque, and I have the pleasure and honor
of interviewing Sam Camilli, class of 73.
To introduce yourself to any reader of the transcript or any listener of the tape, tell about yourself, background, growing up, what did mom and dad do, where'd you go to high school, and so forth.
We're a fifth generation El Paso family.
We were born and raised there.
I went to Austin High School along with my four brothers.
My father and my grandfather were both in the wholesale food business, and we basically grew out of that.
My older brother preceded me at A&M, of which I was responsible for getting him there.
I got there.
Basically, my best friend is a Malooly, and his father

Albert Malooly graduated in 52 and ever since I was you know played baseball played football and he wanted us to just go to A&M he thought he was recruiting everybody for A&M and so he recruited my brother and of course I wanted to go first but Lou my brother got there before me so that's really how I got there I almost didn't get in I didn't have my application until
May 31st when my counselor said, you think you're going where?
I said, well, I'm going to go to A&M.
I said, well, you better get an application in because you won't get there.
And I said, well, Coach Chandler already said I'm getting in, but I said, but I guess I better get my application in.
Had you visited College Station and the campus before you went over to enroll?
Had you ever been there?
Yeah, I went down to see my brother play ball and went to the architecture building.
I wanted to be in architecture, so.
What was your impression when you saw it, in fact?
I loved it.
I mean, my whole life had been for, you know, 12 years of school was basically getting to A&M.
That's what I wanted to do.
So that's really when I got there, I fell in love with it, you know.
My brother loved it, had a good job, you know, a good opportunity there and a good school there.
Now, your brother played?
He played baseball and he played pro baseball.
He went three years and then signed a pro contract.
And was Tom Chandler already there?
Yes, he was our coach, loved him.
Good man, good.
He was a great man, great coach, great human being.
I mean, just absolutely wonderful.
When you went over to enroll in the fall of 69, how did you get there and what did you take with you?
Describe the trip from El Paso to College Station.
Well, I always tell this story about my trip.
When my brother went to A&M, my parents got in the car, loaded him up, took him down there in the car.
Mom made sure he had a place to sleep.
And they were there.
I can't remember what hall they had.
They were torn down the hall.
It was horrible.
finish Fowler Hall, which is where he stayed and I stayed, but this place was really the pits.

And of course my mother saw it, she was all worried about him, you know, she says, oh, he's not going to be happy here, he's going to be, so they, I mean, she just, over and over, both of them just made over, and Tom Chandler said, they'll be fine, the dorm will be finished in a month or so, and they'll be in the new, brand new dorm.
Well, when I went to A&M, my dad handed me a plane ticket,
I took two suitcases and he says, have a good time in college, son.
I don't have to worry about you.
So by, you know, the experience of my brother and Coach Chandler basically saying, hey, don't worry.
Sam's going to be okay.
We got him a room.
He's fine.
He said, call Tom when you get, Coach, when you get there.
He'll come to the airport, pick you up, take you to your dorm.
Well, that's what happened.
I had two suitcases.
I called Coach Chandler.
Coach Chandler showed up.
He picked me up.
He says, is that all you had?
That's all I got?
went to the dorms.
Is that your room?
You're supposed to be here to register or get all your stuff, but I'm taking care of it.
If you have any questions, call me.
We'll see you later.
So, you know, here I am.
I get there.
I went in to the, you know, the down below or the
I can't remember what they called it then, but got my keys, went up to the room, got all set up.
What dorm was it?
Fowler Hall.
Fowler.
And that was the athletic dorm.
That was basically where all the other jocks except the football players.
And they were still in Henderson?
They were still in Henderson.
All right.
What did you, in those two suitcases, what did you take?
Actually, it was funny.
I had all my clothes in one and my stereo in the other.
So I had to have music.
So I played in a band.
I had a bunch of musical background, so I made sure I had music.
And my roommate showed up, John Alvin Woods from Nacogdoches, and he saw I had a stereo.
He said, oh, I'm so happy you brought your stereo.
I said, yeah, you don't know how much trouble it was to pack that thing in that suitcase and make sure it got here okay.
Now, you flew El Paso to Houston.
And a little DC-3 from Houston to College Station.
And Coach Chandler came to meet you.
Yes, he did.
Did you have a scholarship?
No, I didn't have a scholarship, but he made sure I had a room.
And I was on the team, and he got me a few books.
He says, we can help you with your books because that's something that doesn't really take away.

dollars from the university but we can help you with bucks so did he promise you the chance of a scholarship later absolutely he knew my brother my brother was a full full boat and he'd already he'd already uh gone yeah he we're four years apart so he was basically graduated when i got there and he uh he didn't he signed his pro contract his third year so gave coach another scholarship that fourth year um all right um you you weren't in the core how
Describe how you became assimilated into Texas A&M student body.
When did that start?
Oh, the day we went out and started throwing washers out there in front.
I mean, that was just the, you know, you see these two cans in the ground.
Of course, in West Texas, we don't know what washers are.
And all of a sudden, these baseball, well, the rest of the baseball team showed up, you know.
And my brother had a very, um,
Colorful reputation, shall I say?
I'll give you an example.

We went first road trip with Coach Chandler to, I can't remember if it was to Baylor or somewhere, and we went to Luby's to eat, or first to eat, it was Luby's, and he says, okay, everybody's got a limit.
Everybody, you just get whatever you want to eat, except Camille.
He's limited $10.
My brother was known to eat for two or three players.
And of course, everybody had stories about my brother.
But when I got there, they all wanted to see Camille's little brother, Dave Elmendorf, and Long, and those guys.
Who were the big names on the baseball team when you arrived?
Well, Dave Elmendorf, Bob Long was still there.
Butch Gootsman was there.
There was a Georgia Englert I played with who went to the pros.
And several others.
I'll remember their names eventually here.
Describe when you and your roommate got your room set up.
Describe what was in the room and what it looked like.
Literally nothing.
I mean, our stereo.
Because he got to bring more than I did.
Whatever I had is what I had a whole year.
I mean, I didn't have a thing.
And of course, we eventually...
You know, I eventually went out and bought a refrigerator and hid it, and we had a little bit of a toaster oven.
And we hid it because we weren't supposed to have anything in there.
How big was this refrigerator?
It was a little underneath.
We put it underneath the two-by-two, maybe the biggest, underneath the sink.
And we, both of us, liked to eat, as you can tell.
But we used to go out about once a week.

drive the rest of the dorm crazy and we'd get us a couple of steaks at Safeway and we had a little uh for making popcorn we had a hot pad and we brought up got some oil and we cut up some french fries and we'd cook at nine o'clock at night we start cooking those steaks and we'd go to Cebisa the next morning and eat breakfast and John and I used to love to do this we'd walk around behind a bunch of people going to eat breakfast or stand in line
Man, I could have sworn these people, they were in front of us telling us, I could have sworn I smelled steaks last night in the dorm.
Somebody, I mean, we had steaks going.
Somebody had steaks going somewhere.
I was hungry all night.
Well, we just, you know, John, that was just our weekly ritual.
We'd go there.
So that was one of the fun things we did in the dorm that we were never supposed to do.
Right, let's go back to the very, very first.
You didn't go to fish camp?
Didn't go to fish camp.
I don't know if there was fish camp in the city.
Oh yeah, there was.
How did you register and how did you select your courses?
I went to a counselor.
I mean, I basically got there, they gave me the packet, my registration packet down there, all the athletes get it.
So I got my packet, they told me where to go, I went to a counselor, they basically walked me through
Saw what I was weak in, saw what I was strong in, what my major was supposed to be.
And you were going to major in?
Architecture.
It was a lifelong dream.
So I got all registered and it really was not, that was pretty easy for me.
I mean they did a real good job of getting me there.
I was there probably a week before, I was probably there FOW week.
when all the core guys were there.
So none of the athletes, nobody else had showed up.
So I walked campus.
I walked to my classes.
I made sure I knew where this building was and that building was.
So I did all that at their behest.
What impression did the campus make on you, and what made the most impression?
Big.
It was big.
I mean, I never realized.
You know, Austin High School is a big school for a high school.
We had that quad, and we had, you know, we had.
I did not remember it being that big when I went to see my brother play.
So it was very interesting to see the size of it.
Now what seemed new?
Was there anything that seemed real new?
No, the architecture building was brand new when my brother was there.
So, you know, we were real fortunate.
We got into a brand new building.
And, of course, you know, there was still a lot of building going on.
They were building the oceanography building.
They were building, you know, all these things started really coming alive during my
four years there that I saw.
In fact, I worked on the oceanography building.
Do you remember who that counselor was that you?
Not at all.
All right.
Now, first classes.
What were some of those classes you remember the first year?
The first year was, well, I flunked four of them, so I should tell you, history and English
were killers, especially during baseball season.
I ended up having to take English in El Paso to make sure I got back to school next fall.
I took English 101 and History.
Do you remember any of the teachers that first year?
You know, every once in a while their names will flash in front of me, and then somebody will tell me, did you have Song Tso?
You know, I said, you know, I did.
Of course, I had the judge, and I had my geology prof.
I can't remember his name.
He was an older prof, too, and he was funny.
First thing in the day in class, he says, how many athletes do we have in here?
Of course, half the, 90% of the class was athletes trying to get their science.
And he says, okay, I just wanted to know that because I need to,
you know, gauge this class based on what you need to know as opposed to what you, you know, will get you by, so.
As far as you and your buddies were aware, were there any courses that were giveaways to athletes in those days?
We just knew if we took geology, we could get some science credit.
I took a lot of Spanish.
I was fluent in Spanish, so if I needed an A,
which I did several times, I went to Spanish.
And you were fluent in Spanish, not because you'd taken a lot of Spanish, but because you'd grown up in El Paso.
Yeah, we really knew Spanish before we knew English.
My grandfather was an assistant.
And the Spanish prof there was very thrilled to have me there because he was trying to teach, you know, I was kind of his teacher.
Tell them what this means, and then help them out so that they understand this stuff.
Had your older brother given you some advice on how to succeed at A&M?
No.
He was a lot smarter than I was.
I mean, he was a math major and a psychology major, so he really didn't struggle too much.
But did he tell you what to do or not to do?

no of course he was off playing baseball i really didn't see him much and so he just you know he said how you like it i'm doing good he says are you passing i said yeah i'm passing he said that's all that matters as far as you recall what did that first year cost do you remember any oh we have all my old grade slips and i mean i i think it was a thousand dollars the whole year for room board tuition and everything and did you have any spending money yeah my dad put money in the bank which i went through remember how much
He gave me $500 one semester and $600 the next.
As spending money?
As spending money.
And that basically, you know, I had to basically take care of everything, which I thought was pretty good.
And before you left, perhaps related to that money, did your dad give you any guidelines or rules?
No.
I mean, I worked with my dad.
for about seven years.
So he knew my money habits.
I mean, he knew how he paid me.
He saw what I did with my money.
What did he do?
He was in the wholesale food business.
Oh, yeah, that's right.
I was a truck driver.
I was driving a truck delivering food since I was 15.
And he, you know, he resigned my paycheck every week.
And I think I was the only person that I never had one vacation.
I went to college for five years or four and a half.
And every vacation, I went home to work.
And my dad said, this is your trade-off.
And every summer I went back and worked for him.
I didn't work really in my field.
And you assumed you were going to graduate in what period of time?
Well, I thought it was five years.
I guess one of my rudest awakenings at A&M was I went to my first architecture class, and Dean Romick was there.
And all the freshmen walked in, and he went up to the podium.
He says, y'all are here to be architects?
He says, yes.
He says, well, I'm here to tell you this is the wrong place to be.
He says, you do not need to be in the architecture profession.
The architecture profession is dead.
Architects, you know, are a dying breed.
You're never going to make any money.
You're never going to be successful.
He says, you're going to be frustrated your whole life.
And he says, and that's why we're changing this department.
So all of us are saying, wait a minute.
We've got our five-year plan here written down on our schedule sheets.
And you're telling us, you know, we've got our book and everything else.
He says, yeah, you're going to be
You are now going to be considered ED students, which are environmental design.
We want you to learn design.
We want you to learn all these things that architects never learn.
They learn how to draw straight lines.
We want them to learn how to design first.
We left.
Of course, we're all scratching our heads.
About half of the guys said, I'm out of here.
I'm going to go to UT or go to some other schools.
So as, you know, we were the guinea pig.
I think our class was the first ED class that graduated, and the goal was to get us into graduate school.
Well, that's real good if, you know, and I was.
I was accepted to graduate school.
I was planning on going to graduate school.
Unfortunately, I had a father and a fianc that both said I was having too much fun in college.
And one of them wanted to get married, and one of them said,
You're on your own, son.
Your younger brother now is in college.
So it was one of those things.
And the degree is not, I'm not doing what I really wanted to do, but it really helped me focus on what I needed to do.
My talent is in construction, not in design.
So that's really where it led me, and that's what I'm doing.
Now, in those first months or that first year, was there anyone in E.D.
or architecture, whichever we title it, was there anyone to whom you began to turn for advice and direction?
Not until my second year.
The first year was pretty much.
Who was it then, the second year?
It was Larry Priesmeier.
He and I, you know, he was the first one that said, Sam, you're not a designer.
He says, you don't have

you know you're not an off the wall type guy you know that these big firms he says you're he says you know what you'd be great if i had a firm you're a nut bolt guy you'd be drawing door jams your whole life because you can do it you you know but give you something real out you know something out there to draw he says you'll you'll struggle for 20 years he says you need to get and they didn't really have a construction program at that time it was it was just that was it so he says you need to concentrate on these things
So, you know, he really kind of led me to get more into design build where I could, you know, design metal buildings and, you know, warehouses.
And that's really where
Where he led me so you need to learn how to build these things and you need to be a contractor In that first year or two were there any other?
experiences you remember with somebody that were important As you look back I
I can't remember the prof, but he was from Santa Fe, and he spent a lot of, it was one of those things that he saw the same thing in me that was in him.
He was more of an outdoor person and everything else.
That's what he told me.
He says, you do not fit the mold of somebody being in the office.
He says, I've been in the field for 8 or 9, 10 years.
I can tell you right now.
He left the architecture field and went to Santa Fe to live and work in the mountains and everything else.
He says, I can sense that
you're more of a hands-on guy.
He said, you don't, you know, you work with your hands, you do things with your hands.
Because I built great models.
I was a real good model builder.
I could really do the building part.
Everybody wanted me as a partner so that I could help them build stuff.
They could design it, I could build it.
So as we teamed up on teams, you know, I always got the three guys that couldn't put a nail in a two-by-four to help, you know, and I would go build a thing and they'd just tell me what to build.
So that's kind of how
as we got to that year, the third year earlier.
All right, back to the first year.
During those first weeks, months, how did you and your freshman buddies learn about A&M traditions and all that?
Most of them, I should have been at an advantage with my brother being there, but I was at a disadvantage in that everybody there seemed to know what to do, where to go, everything.
So I followed.
I did a lot of following.

you know, like most people, and being from West Texas, way out there where I was, it was strange because I caught, my wife still has this in a letter, when there wasn't a football game on a weekend, there was two people in the dorm, me and somebody else on the back side, a swimmer from somewhere that didn't have transportation, so everybody else went home.
You know, the campus was basically evacuated except the people from Mexico or, you know, the Far East or
You know, so I basically learned real quick, you know, you need to make friends.
If you don't want to spend every weekend that there ain't a football game on this campus.
So I started making friends.
I started, you know, enjoying going back to the little city down in Dallas and Waxahachie and places like that to people's houses and coming back to A&M.
And as you make friends, you start making friends.
Like half of the friends that I met on the baseball team all had friends in the Corps.
Mm-hmm.
So they're all coming over here crying, you know, the blues, you know, in their uniforms.
They'd hide in our dormitory room.
You know, these guys, I mean, what are you doing over here?
I need to stay in here for about four hours.
Just leave me alone.
I'm in class.
I'm in study hall.
I'm doing something.
Just leave us alone.
So they'd show up in the uniforms, and pretty soon we had nine or ten or twelve guys, you know, in the Corps over there visiting us.
So we'd start learning about the Corps and, of course, how hard it was and,
how lucky we were that we weren't in the corps and those type of things.
But we didn't venture much to the quad.
I mean, as athletes, if you weren't in the corps, we just didn't venture over there too much.
Now you all ate, you and your roommate ate at Sabeasa.
Describe the routine at Sabeasa for civilian soldiers.
Well, you walk in, drop your briefcase or your books and get in line.
For me, it was, you know, strange to eat just at, you know, it wasn't like high school where you all had your same buddies.
Every day was seeing it with somebody different or saw somebody different.
And it was pretty much first come, first serve, you know, very unregulated, regimented.
I didn't like the idea that you couldn't eat all day long, but, you know, you had to get there in time.
Did you think the food was good?
I thought the food was great.
But any food to me is great.
Was there, among you non-Corps members, was there mischief in the dining hall?
Oh, there's lots of butter patties on the ceiling.
We had a couple of pretty good food fights.
Over what?
Somebody said, pass something.
I can't remember what it was.
And you put out your hand, and you got a, you know,
You got a whole douse of sugar or something in your hand and you throw it back and pretty soon it just gets going back and forth.
Somebody will fling a butter patty at you across the room and you try to figure out who it was.
And how many people maybe were involved in a food fight?
Well, eventually everybody, I think.
And was there any punishment?
No, a lot of us had to clean up stuff.
Coach Chandler showed up one day and said, I understand everybody had a good time last night at supper.
He says, we're going to clean up over there.
So, you know, it was the baseball players against the swimmers and the track guys one time.
I know that.
We all had supper, and basically everybody was there at the bus.
Did he say, it's not going to happen again?
No.
He just said, you're going to go clean it up.
And he told them, he said, you all don't touch that stuff.
He says, I'm sending some boys back over there.
They're going to clean up for you.
So we got to clean up.
All right.
What did you soon assume to be some guidelines for you about going to class and behavior and dress and homework and so forth?
My roommate wouldn't agree to it, but I learned real quick you try to get as much done before you got back to the dorm as possible.
I did, where I went to the library.
Because once I got back to the dorm,
You know, studying was out the window, you know, and everybody playing cards and playing baseball games in the rooms and stuff like that.
So if I wanted, I lived in the architecture building.
So basically, I mean, I stayed there as long as I possibly could because once I got back to my dorm room, I never cracked a book.
I mean, as an honest to God, I never read a book.
If I was going to read or study, I'd go to the library.
And this is the old Cushing Library.
This is the old Cushing Library.
I fell asleep many times in there.
Did you ever know of any mischief there?
No.
I never saw and I never did any.
Nobody else has either.
I just don't, you know, you just went there.
Everybody was too busy trying to get their studying done.
I guess they felt the same way once they got back to their dorm.
Give me a description of a typical class day.
What time did you get up?
What did you do when?
From getting up to going to bed, describe a typical day.
Usually I always got an 8 o'clock class.
Architecture classes are four hours.
So baseball, we always had to have that class first in the morning.
So I'd get up, you know, John and I would get up and go to breakfast, and I'd just take off from there and go down to the architecture building.
I'd stay there for three hours.
Then I hit my next, you know, I had a class.
I never had a, my first freshman year, I never had an hour in between classes because we had fall ball and we had to be out there by 2 o'clock.
So I had class 11, I had class 12, I had class 1 by 2 o'clock.
I was hooking it up to the baseball field to get my cleats on and my stuff, get ready to play ball, and we'd finish that up.
And when fall ball wasn't there, we just basically, when we weren't playing baseball, we'd go back to the dorm or go work out.
We'd go back to the dorm and have supper.
Everybody walked to supper together, and about 8 o'clock, we'd start playing.
I mean, guys would start playing cards and
At what time would y'all go to bed?
Midnight.
Did you go to class every day?
I mean, I had class scheduled every day.
I didn't make it every day.
Oh, you did cut some classes?
Oh, yeah.
I was right on the ragged edge.
My freshman year, I was, you know, half the time I was
Especially English and history.
Do you remember who you had for history?
I could probably look at my records, but I don't remember who it was.
Because I was still teaching a big fresh 105 at 8 o'clock on Tuesday and Thursday over in either in physics or in Zachary.
I might have had you.
I was a horrible student.
Did you turn to anybody for academic advice during that semester?
Hey, what do I do?
Well, Coach Chandler got me help all the time.
He knew all the freshmen were struggling.
He knew I was going to struggle.
He warned me.
He says, it's almost impossible for an architecture student to be an athlete.
He says, they demand more of your time to be down there in the labs than we do.
He says, they want you there.
learning, you know, everything.
So he said, you're going to struggle.
And for two years, I did struggle.
And then I decided it was enough baseball.
It was either, you know,
One time I had to go, and it was obviously baseball.
During that first year, did you and your buddies go to Yale practice?
Oh, yeah, we had Yale practice right out in front of our dorm.
Okay.
Several times.
Okay.
So, yeah, we... What about midnight Yale practice?
Yes, we'd go to midnight Yale practice, and we were known to dive off the three-meter, three, is it the three-meter board?
Mm-hmm.
The platform.
Mm-hmm.
It was condemned.
That was one of our, we'd go over there with the swimmers and dive off that thing at 2 or 3 in the morning after midnight.
Campus police come screaming down there, what are y'all, you guys, that thing is condemned, it's going to fall down.
And what would y'all be wearing when you did that?
Our clothes, full clothes, whatever we had on at the time.
They just come by, hey, we're going to go die.
You guys want to come?
All right, now that sounds like that might have been physically dangerous.
Looking back on it, did you all do any other pranks that you now realize were dangerous?
Oh, I wouldn't call it dangerous, but I think we had a band my second year over there.
Baseball players had a
Charlie Jenkins was a drummer.
Had another guy down the road play saxophone, I played guitar, and we got a couple of core guys for the band that wanted to play, and we started playing one night.
It was 11, 11 o'clock, 12 o'clock, we're out on the stoop, you know, we're just rocking along, just had everybody downstairs below just having a good old time.
All of a sudden, one guy stopped playing, the other guy stopped playing, and
Because half us are in the room, half us are out of the room.
We're trying to figure out how all these people are kind of moving down the stoop.
And in comes Gene Stallings.
And he says, boys, you sound great.
He says, I love the music.
I said, but I got some players across the way that need to get their sleep because they're going to play a football game on Saturday.
He says, I don't want you to stop ever playing the music.
I just want you to stop tonight.
So he walked, you know, and everybody, you know, we're just all shaking in our boots.
Chandler's going to hear about it now.
And, you know, of course, Tom had it.
I said, I heard you guys were serenading the football players the other night, boys.
He said, we're not going to have that again.
I said, we'll stop early, Coach.
We'll stop early.
So that was not a, it was a very threatening thing because Gene was a man of very few words.
And all he had to do, and everybody was starting to pack up their stuff.
We knew we had done something wrong, so we just started putting our stuff away.
We had a little contest one year, and these were the older baseball players when I was there.
The football players would get on top of Henderson on the roof.
And we'd get on top of Fowler on the roof with our golf clubs and our golf balls.
Yeah, we'd have little...
I wouldn't say mortar launches.
